  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1929081434" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1929081434" />
    <a title="Phrynne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8655084-phrynne"><img alt="Phrynne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640891977p2/8655084.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1929081434?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phrynne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phrynne" href="/user/show/8655084-phrynne">Phrynne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1929081434" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8511917113650276616">An apparently simple tale of a woman&apos;s life from early hardship to later success, yet nothing about it is actually simple. Lucy Barton tells much of her story from a hospital bed where she has endless time to think back to her childhood and her life since. She recalls and mentions many things in passing and leaves much to the reader&apos;s imagination. A snippet of information here, a hint of something there and we are eventually pretty sure her childhood was not just deprived but also abusive. <br/>By th</span>
  <span id="freeText8511917113650276616" style="display:none">An apparently simple tale of a woman's life from early hardship to later success, yet nothing about it is actually simple. Lucy Barton tells much of her story from a hospital bed where she has endless time to think back to her childhood and her life since. She recalls and mentions many things in passing and leaves much to the reader's imagination. A snippet of information here, a hint of something there and we are eventually pretty sure her childhood was not just deprived but also abusive. <br />By the end of the book Lucy is obviously someone to be admired for her ability to not only survive but to rise above her situation. I enjoyed her story very much and also enjoyed the author's deft, understated style where nothing was actually explained yet so much was said. <br />My first book by this author but not my last!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8511917113650276616" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

